To derive a two‐token string under S→NT1 NT7, NT1 must yield the first token (t39) and NT7 the second (t69).  
• NT1’s terminal productions are only {t32, t42, t25, t14, t38, t79, t44, t33}, so it cannot produce t39.  
Hence S cannot generate “t39 t69”.

We check the unique way to split “t25 t68 t35” under S→NT1 NT7 (CNF forces a binary split).  
Try NT1 ⇒ “t25” and NT7 ⇒ “t68 t35”:  
• NT1→’t25’ exists.  
• NT7→NT3 NT5 exists, with NT3→’t68’ and NT5→’t35’.  

Hence S ⇒ NT1 NT7 ⇒ “t25” “t68 t35” and the string is generated.  
Yes

To get three tokens under S → NT1 NT7, NT1 must produce the first token and NT7 the remaining two.  

1. NT1 → 't25' (given), so NT1 ⇒ t25.  
2. We need NT7 ⇒ t68 t61. Under its binary productions,  
   NT7 → NT3 NT5  
     NT3 → 't68'  
     NT5 → 't61'  

So NT7 ⇒ NT3 NT5 ⇒ 't68' 't61'.  

Putting it together:  
S → NT1 NT7 ⇒ t25 (t68 t61) ⇒ t25 t68 t61.  

Yes

We can do a small CYK‐style check on the 4‐token string t38 t25 t25 t10 under S→NT1 NT7:

1. Positions 1..4 are t38, t25, t25, t10.
2. NT1 only ever produces a single terminal, and indeed NT1→'t38', so NT1 can cover the first token t38.
3. That forces NT7 to cover tokens 2..4 = t25 t25 t10. We check that with binary rules:

   - t25 at position 2 can be NT0 or NT1; t25 at position 3 likewise NT0 or NT1; t10 at position 4 is NT5.
   - Positions 3–4 (t25 t10): splitting at k=3 gives NT0 NT5 ⇒ NT9→NT0 NT5, so NT9 covers 3–4.
   - Positions 2–4: splitting at k=2 gives NT0 (for t25) and NT9 (for t25 t10) ⇒ NT7→NT0 NT9, so NT7 covers 2–4.

Thus

 S
 → NT1 NT7
 → 't38' NT7
 → 't38' NT0 NT9
 → 't38' 't25' NT9
 → 't38' 't25' NT0 NT5
 → 't38' 't25' 't25' 't10'

so the grammar does generate the string.  
Yes

To derive a length‐4 string from S in CNF, we must split as

S → NT1 NT7

NT1 can only produce exactly one terminal. The only way to match the first terminal t25 is

NT1 → 't25'.

That leaves NT7 to produce the remaining three terminals: t8 t11 t70. A small CYK‐style check shows no way for NT7 to generate that length‐3 substring (all binary splits fail, and no NT7→… chain produces exactly t8 t11 t70). Hence the string is not in the language.

To decide if S ⇒* t38 t58 t12 t10 t42, we run CYK:

1) Terminals → nonterminals:

 position 1: t38 → {NT1}  
 position 2: t58 → {NT0}  
 position 3: t12 → {NT0, NT3, NT9}  
 position 4: t10 → {NT5}  
 position 5: t42 → {NT9, NT1}  

2) Fill length 2 spans:

(1,2): {NT1}×{NT0} → ∅  
(2,3): {NT0}×{NT0,NT3,NT9} → NT7 (by NT7→NT0 NT9)  
(3,4): {NT0,NT3,NT9}×{NT5} → NT9 (NT9→NT0 NT5), NT7 (NT7→NT3 NT5)  
(4,5): {NT5}×{NT9,NT1} → ∅  

3) Length 3:

(1,3): {NT1}×{NT7} → S (by S→NT1 NT7)  
(2,4): {NT0}×{NT9,NT7} and {NT7}×{NT5} → NT7  
(3,5): {NT9,NT7}×{NT9,NT1} → NT7  

4) Length 4:

(1,4): {NT1}×{NT7} → S  
(2,5): {NT7}×{NT9,NT1} → NT7  

5) Length 5:

(1,5): {NT1}×{NT7} → S  

Since S covers the entire input, the string is in the language.  
Yes

We can apply the CYK algorithm. Number the input tokens w₁…w₆ as

 w₁ = t33  
 w₂ = t12  
 w₃ = t54  
 w₄ = t60  
 w₅ = t61  
 w₆ = t42  

First, fill the diagonal with all NT’s that produce each terminal:

 w₁=t33 ⇒ NT1, NT2  
 w₂=t12 ⇒ NT0, NT3, NT9  
 w₃=t54 ⇒ NT2, NT9  
 w₄=t60 ⇒ NT2, NT9  
 w₅=t61 ⇒ NT2, NT5  
 w₆=t42 ⇒ NT1, NT9  

Next we use the binary rules

  S  → NT1 NT7  
  NT3→ NT3 NT2  
  NT9→ NT0 NT5  
  NT7→ NT3 NT5  
  NT7→ NT0 NT9  
  NT7→ NT7 NT1  

to fill in spans of length 2,…,6.  The only non‐empty length‑2 cell is

  span(2,3) = {NT3, NT7}  coming from  
    (NT3,NT2)→NT3 and (NT0,NT9)→NT7.

Continuing in this way up to the full span (1,6), one finds

  span(1,6) contains S,

since

  w₁=w[1,1] ⇒ NT1
  w[2,6] ⇒ NT7
  (NT1,NT7)→S

Thus S ⇒* t33 t12 t54 t60 t61 t42, so the answer is

Yes

To generate the six‐token string under S→NT1 NT7, NT1 must cover the first token and NT7 the remaining five.  NT1 only ever produces a single terminal, and it indeed can produce t38.  But NT7 cannot produce the five‐token sequence t68 t25 t58 t44 t17: a straightforward CYK check shows no way to build any length‑2 or larger substring from NT7 using its binary rules (all length‑2 spans are empty in the DP).  Hence NT7 cannot cover the last five tokens, so the string is not in the language.

By a straightforward CYK‐style check one finds:

1. S → NT1 NT7, and NT1 ⇒ t32.  
2. The remaining substring t68 t14 t17 t44 t38 t79 (length 6) is generated by NT7:
   - NT7 ⇒ NT7 NT1 ⇒ NT7 NT1 NT1 ⇒ … ⇒ t68 t14 t17 t44 t38 t79.  
   (In particular, NT7 repeatedly uses NT7→NT7 NT1 to peel off t79, t38, t44, and then NT7→NT3 NT5 to handle t68 t14 t17.)

Hence the grammar does generate the string.  
Yes

We can see immediately that the start rule is  
  S → NT1 NT7  
and in Chomsky normal form NT1 only ever produces a single terminal.  Hence any string of length >1 must have its first terminal come from NT1.  Our string begins with t53, but NT1 can only produce one of  
  t32, t42, t25, t14, t38, t44, t79 or t33.  
Since t53 ∉ {t32, t42, t25, t14, t38, t44, t79, t33}, no derivation from S can yield this string.

 S → NT1 NT7  
NT1 has no binary expansions, so it yields exactly one terminal—namely the first token of the string. Here the first token is “t21”, but NT1’s terminal productions are  
 {t32, t42, t25, t14, t38, t79, t44, t33}  
which does not include t21. Hence no derivation is possible.

After the initial S→NT1 NT7, NT1 must consume exactly one token. Since our string begins with “t42” and NT1→t42 is valid, we’re left asking whether NT7 ⇒* the 10‐token tail

  t70 t26 t56 t25 t82 t58 t74 t82 t83 t38.

NT7’s only multi‐token derivations are of the form

  NT7 ⇒ … ⇒ (base) followed by k single‐terminal NT1 “tails.”

The base can be one terminal (e.g. NT7→t70) or two nonterminals (NT3 NT5 or NT0 NT9).  
• If base = t70, then the remaining 9 tokens must all come from NT1’s terminals {t32,t42,t25,t14,t38,t79,t44,t33}. But the very next token is t26, which NT1 cannot produce.  
• If base = NT3 NT5 or NT0 NT9, the first token of that base must be t70. Neither NT3 nor NT0 can derive t70 as their leftmost terminal.  

No other CNF split can align. Hence NT7 cannot generate that 10‐token tail, and S cannot generate the full string.  

No

After running the CYK algorithm there is no way to build an NT7 over the entire suffix 2…11 (the only NT7 spans are (4,5) and then (4,6)), so S→NT1 NT7 cannot cover all 11 symbols. Hence the string is not in the language.

can never cover the 11‐token input: NT1 only ever produces single terminals (no binary rules), and the very first token t73 is not in NT1, so there is no way to split the input into NT1·NT7.

– NT9 on span (6–7)  
– S  on span (2–3)

No other binary combinations ever produce NT1 or NT7 on any span longer than 1, so there is no way to build S→NT1 NT7 over the entire length 11. Hence the string is not generated.

But NT1 has no binary productions—NT1 can only rewrite to a single terminal.  Hence in any S→NT1 NT7 derivation, NT1 must generate exactly one terminal (the very first token).  Here the first token is t70, and t70 appears only on the right‐hand side of NT7→'t70', never on an NT1 production.  Therefore NT1 cannot yield the first token, so S cannot derive the entire string.

1) NT7→'t7'|'t69'|'t80'|'t31'|'t70'|'t44'|'t20'|'t83'|'t6'  
2) NT7→NT3 NT5  
3) NT7→NT0 NT9  
4) NT7→NT7 NT1

In any of these cases the rightmost nonterminal in the last step must generate the final terminal of the string.  
– If NT7→terminal, none of its terminal options is t68.  
– If NT7→NT3 NT5, the last terminal comes from NT5, whose terminal set is {t84,t61,t66,t10,t17,t74,t35,t21,t8}, not t68.

– If NT7→NT7 NT1, the final terminal must lie in NT1’s set {t32,t25,t42,t14,t38,t79,t44,t33}, again not t68.

Since the given string ends in t68, no derivation in this grammar can produce it. Answer: No
